Hello Ulm Bluehawk Parents,
ü§ìWe have a few important upcoming dates to remind you of.

ü§ìThe last day to drop off packets and or school work to be graded is Monday, May 18th from 5 PM to 6:30 PM.

ü§ìBelonging and report card pick up day is Thursday, May 21st from 8 am to 4 pm.

ü•≥Tell the kids to wear their Bluehawk gear so you can take a last day of school photo!

ü§ìIf you have recently received a Montana O P I Student Attendance Agreement for the school year 2020-2021 please remember that this form needs to be filled out for each of your students. The deadline to return it is May 21st, 2020. If you live outside of the Ulm School District you would have received this form.

ü§ìPlease note the teaching staff will be monitoring the amount of people in and out of the building to ensure we are all being as safe as possible. Please be prepared to wash and sanitize upon arrival and exit of the building.

Last night the Ulm School Board voted to continue with the school closure for the remainder of the current school year.

Distance learning with your child's teacher will continue for the remainder of this school year.

Your child's teacher will communicate with you regarding the next homework pickup dates.

In the meantime if you have any questions please contact me at 4 0 6 5 7 9 5 4 6 9.

Thank you for your time and please tell your children how much all the Ulm School Staff misses them.

Hello Ulm School Parents. This is a message from your school principal Russ McDaniel.

I would like to provide you with an update on the current school closure and next steps for our district with the announcement from the Governor yesterday. The school will remain closed until May 7th as directed by the Governor.

On Tuesday, April 28th, 2020 at 6:30 pm there will be an Ulm School Board meeting held via Zoom. During this meeting you will have an opportunity to share your feedback regarding next steps. Please see the Ulm School website at ulmschools.com for the link to this meeting. Click on the School Board Tab on the website and you will find the link to the Zoom meeting.

In the meantime if you have any questions please contact me at (406) 579-5469. Thank you for your time and please tell those kids how much all the Ulm School Staff misses them.

post_text: This is Russ McDaniel. I‚Äôm calling with an update in light of the recent confirmed cases now here in Cascade County. I would like to stress safety at tomorrow morning‚Äôs pick up of school materials between 8 and 10am. We ask for your patience as just one person per family will be allowed in the building to pick up materials as we work together to follow all precautionary guidelines. Further, if you would like to stay in your car, please call the main office at (406) 866-3313 and someone will deliver your child‚Äôs materials to you. Keep in mind this is a grab and go process. If tomorrow‚Äôs pick up does not work for you, or if you or anyone in your household is experiencing a fever or cough, please stay home. Let us know and we will make other arrangements for you. Thank you for your cooperation. On a final note we are still offering our food services for any students needing breakfast, lunch or both. Please call me if interested and we can make those arrangements, (406) 579-5469. Thank you and stay healthy.

Family Connections Montana
March 19 at 3:23 PM ¬∑

Hey Everyone!

We know that it's hard work caring for young children and we so appreciate our early care and education providers that do so everyday! We also know that right now it may be even more stressful as we navigate uncharted territory. In addition, for those staying at home it can also be stressful and a little chaotic if it's not the norm.

Family Connections wants to help! We will be hosting a live story time every business day, beginning tomorrow, March 20, at 11 am MST. While we can't come in and sub for you or give you a break in-person, we are hoping that we can give you 5-10 minutes of break that you can sit with the children and just breathe.

Stories will be appropriate for children 0-5 and will follow with a related learning activity.

Hope this helps, even just a little, and brings a smile to your face and the children in your care!

Hello Bluehawk Nation!

We thought it might be fun to post a daily challenge for families on our page. You can then post a picture or write in the comments how you completed the challenge that day. This is a completely voluntary challenge. Our goal was to give families an idea of something to do (if they need it) and connect our Ulm family online.

If you can not complete challenge due to work or other circumstances then no worries! Thank you for your patience and flexibility during this crazy time at our school.

Like our post, share, and comment to tell us your thoughts.

This is Russ McDaniel your school principal. Governor Bullock has made the decision to close schools across Montana. Schools will be closed for two weeks due to COVID19. This closure is not due to an outbreak.
Our food services will be in operation if necessary. If you would like your child to receive breakfast or lunch please text me. Public access to the school is prohibited without an appointment. Contact me directly at (406) 579 - 5469 if you need an appointment.
Thank you

On a daily basis our school building provides us with many things. Shelter, Food, and a comfortable place to teach and learn to mention a few.

After that day is over for the students and staff, Big Sky Cleaners comes in and cleans up the school and preps the building for another day of success.

In addition to their nightly efforts Big Sky Cleaners will be spending extra time this weekend disinfecting, cleaning, and sanitizing our beloved building and all of its well loved surfaces.

post_text:
A Science Fair Update from Mrs. Rumney:

Thank you for all of your help, patience, and understanding during my occasional descents into madness. I could not have done any of this Science Fair without your support.

Regional Science Fair Results:
Eighth graders Amelea McKamey, Juliann Phillips, and Destiny Turan each earned a gold award and qualified to attend the State Science Fair.

Seventh graders Cameron Gaines, Kylee Hooper, Adalynn Jensen, and Sheyla Marquis each earned a silver award.
Sixth graders Beau Davis, Keegan Hawn, Ashlyn Korst, Grace Lamb, Trent Leardini, Isaac McKamey, and Asher Nelson each earned a gold award.

Sixth graders Brandon Bronson and Jaxon Coates each earned a silver award.

Juliann Phillips and Ashlyn Korst each won the Broadcom Masters award. Adalynn Jenson and Juliann Phillips each one a certificate of merit.

Juliann Phillips took 3rd place overall in the biological division for eighth grade. Ashlynn Korst won 1st place overall in the physical division for sixth grade.

ABC Academic Booster Club Presents:
üí≤üí≤üí≤A Penny War üí≤üí≤üí≤
March 2nd - March 13

Bring Pennies to add to your classroom‚Äôs penny jar.
Each penny is worth one point.
If you bring any coins or bills that are not pennies those count against your pennies.

Ex. 8th grade class has collected 100 pennies = 100 points. Early Kindergarten puts one quarter = 25 points in the 8th grade jar. This takes the 8th grade total down to 75 points. So you want to put the pennies in your own jar and the other money into a different classroom jar.

The class that has the highest amount of points will be awarded a St. Patrick‚Äôs Day Float Party on March 17th, 2020. Their classroom teacher will also win a huge basket of prizes donated from True Brew, 3-D International Restaurant, and Staples!

Money collected from this fundraising event will be used on Track and Field Day 2020!
